{"/service/ndnp/mimtptc/batch_mimtptc_inkster_ver01/data/sn88063294/00340589075/1945081801/0517.xml":{"full_text":"A Challenge to Free* Men\nT'HERE is a great challenge to the\nfreedom loving people of America\nand a great decision to be made by\nthem in this hour of victory and\npeace, as Mr. Herbert Hoover ear\nnestly observed in his address before\nthe lowa Association of Southern\nCalifornia at Long Beach.\nThe end of the war will not bring\ntranquillity and surcease from danger\nand respite from responsibility and\nrelief from burdens, even to the vic\ntorious nations \u2014least of all to the\nAmerican nation which has done so\nmuch and paid so much for victory\nand peace.\nIn the wake of war all over the\nworld, as Mr. Hoover said, it is not\nhuman FREEDOM that is evolving\nfrom the bitter years of conflict, for\neither the victors or the vanquished.\nThe nations of Europe, whatever\ntheir previous conditions and aspira\ntions have been, are not turning their\nnewly won and hard won peace to the\nattainment of a FREE condition of\nlife or to the realization of their aspi\nrations for a free existence.\n\u201cToday, communism or CREEP\nING SOCIALISM is sweeping over\nEurope,\u201d said Mr. Hoover.\n\u201cA score of Fascist nations have\nshifted to communism.\n*Half a dozen nations once lib\nerty-loving are shifting to socialism\nWhatever else these nations are\ngetting out of the war and the peace\nfollowing it, they are not getting\nFREEDOM\n\u201cThey all have a common base in\nbureaucratic power over the liberties\nand economic life of the people as\nMr. Hoover remarked.\n\u201cIn the extreme form they leave\nlittle of free speech, free press, free\nassembly or independent justice.\n\u201cThe less violent forms claim that\ngovernment can dictate or operate\neconomic life and still preserve per\nsonal liberty.\n\u201cBut history shows, over and over\nagain, that bureaucrats, to STAY in\npower and to enforce their ideas,\nmust in the end dominate the mak\ning of laws, the press, the courts and\nthe police.\n\u201cInevitably and invariably the\nOur At laul i\n'THE casual remarks by President\nTruman in his Berlin speech con\ncerning American territorial acquisi\ntions after and in consequence of the\npresent war continue to be the sub\nject of much speculation and some\ndispute\u2014and it would be a mistake\nto avoid or suppress the issue.\nIt has been said in explanation of\nthe President\u2019s remarks\u2014to the ef\nfect that America wants \u201cnot one\npiece of territory\u2019\u2019 out of the war\u2014\nthat he was talking solely of the\nEuropean war, and had no intention\nof foreclosing the United States\nagainst permanent possession of the\nstrategic Pacific islands which Japan\nfortified and used against us in\nthis war.\nBut this is by no means a satis\nfactory explanation.\nThe matter of the Pacific islands\nis surely a vital matter, but it lacks\na great deal of covering the whole\nsubject of possible and proper terri\ntorial acquisitions in which there is a\nvital American interest.\nThe European war, fully as much\nas the Pacific war, emphasized the\ninherent danger to the United States\nin having land masses adjacent to\nthe American mainland either enemy\ncontrolled or of easy access to future\nenemies.\nThe great land mass of Green\nland, for instance, is intimately ad\njacent to the American mainland,\nand for all practical purposes is an\nessential PART of the North Ameri\ncan continent- and is surely that for\nall MILITARY purposes.\nThe smaller, but equally strategic\nland mass of Iceland is inseparable\nfrom the defensive zone of the Ameri\ncan mainland.\nThe American government took\nfull account of the military impor\ntance of Greenland and Iceland in the\nEuropean war, and in fact, before\nour formal involvement in the con\nflict.\nAmerican garrisons and installa\ntions were established in the two\nislands in sufficient time and strength\nto make them the keystones of our\nAtlantic defenses and contributed\n8-C\nTHE DETROIT TIMES\ntotalitarian \u2018liberals\u2019 find themselves\nwhittling away the freedom of men.\n\u201cTheir Utopia is a will-o\u2019-the\nwisp that leads implacably to the\nswamps of serfdom.\u2019\u2019\nTHEREIN, according to Mr.\nHoover, lies the challenge to\nAmerica and the requirement for our\ngreat decision as the war draws to a\nclose.\nAre we, too, going to shift from\nthe free way of life to either commu\nnism or creeping socialism\u2014both of\nwhich lead to the same enslaved con\ndition of mankind, and are thus es\nsentially the SAME THING?\nIf so, we must be prepared to\nabandon and see destroyed the\nAMERICAN way of life which, as\nMr. Hoover defines it, \u201cacknowl\nedges the fatherhood of God and the\ndignity of man.\n\u201cIt knows no rank, no caste, no\nexclusions,\u2019\u2019 he reminds us.\n\u201cIt recognizes man\u2019s right to per\nsonality, to freedom of choice, to\nfreedom of will and judgment; the\nright to think, to believe, to have\nfaith, to dream, to speak, to write.\n\u201cIt insists that these inalienable\nfreedoms of mind and spirit came\nfrom the Creator himself, NOT\nFROM THE STATE.\n\u201cIt is the duty of the state to\nprotect these rights, not to coerce\nthem.\u2019\u2019\nAll over the world where commu\nnistic and socialistic totalitarianism\nis becoming- dominant, and even in\nthe United States where it has strong\nadvocacy, persuasive and persistent\nmen are calling it LIBERALISM to\npromote this regimented condition\nfor human beings and REACTION to\noppose it.\nBut the vast majority of the\nAmerican people, faithful to the\nprinciples and ideals of their fathers\nand true to their own natural and\nwholesale AMERICAN ASPIRA\nTIONS, will say with Herbert\nHoover:\n\u201cIf it be reactionary to be for\nFREE MEN, then I shall be proud of\nthat title for my remaining days.\n\u201cAs a matter of fact, it is the\nonly true LIBERALISM\nv Defenses\nsubstantially to the shortening and\nwinning of the European war.\nIt was only by virtue of our\nprompt and decisive action in this re\nspect that German occupation of\nGreenland and Iceland was not\nachieved, as the German high com\nmand contemplated\u2014in which event\nthe course of the European war would\nhave been vastly different, and much\nless to our advantage.\n\nCCORDINGLY, Representative\nGearhart of California is spon\nsoring a movement in Congress for\nPERMANENT American control of\nthe islands\u2014not through conquest or\nany other form of aggression, but by\nthe peaceful means of purchase and\nannexation.\n\u201cIn advocating the acquirement\nof Greenland and Iceland by the\nways of peace,\u201d he explains, \u201cI am\nlooking forward to the time when\nour possession of them may prevent\nwhat we are going through now in\nthe Pacific, may forestall the need\nof capturing them from an enemy\nthat might otherwise seize them in\na few hours by aerial invasion.\u2019\u2019\nGreenland is a possession of Den\nmark, which has little economic use\nfor the great island and is utterly\nincapable of its defense \u2014and Den\nmark has already sold us the Virgin\nIslands, having found herself in a\nsimilarly unprofitable and untenable\nsituation there.\nIceland, as Mr. Gearhart says, is\n\u201ceminently tit to join the United\nStates,\u201d having been virtually \u201ca\nsovereign land since 1918.\u201d\nOf course, the proposed territorial\nacquisitions in the Atlantic would not\nbe made by force or conquest, but by\npeaceful means \u2014and accordingly,\nPresident Truman was quite right\nin saying that we did not fight in\nEurope \u201cfor conquest.\u201d\nBut he should refrain from fore\nclosing the United States against\npeaceful and wise and essential terri\ntorial acquisitions, either in the Pa\ncific or the Atlantic\u2014an intention\nmany commentators are able and\nwilling to read in his Berlin speech.\nAug 1945\nPah\nMALLOX\nI\n\u2014Behind\nI The News\nWASHINGTON. Aug. 17- A\ntendency to hold back de\nmobilization to cushion the\nshock of r**conversmn haa long\nbepn visible through Mr. T*ru\ni mans actions or lack of them.\nThus his first peacetime an\nnouncemcnt continued the draft\nfor the youngest class, and con\ntemplated a discharge plan\nJ spread over 12 to 18 months of\nonly two-thirds of the war army,\nand an even more cautious re\nlaxation of navy strength.\nOur obligations in occupations\nand f>eace-making are mentioned\nas the reason The unsettled\nstate of the world is another,\nalthough not mentioned,\nI suspect Mr. Truman re\nsolved all doubts in favor of high\nbudgets for the army during the\nlatter davs of the war for the\nsame purpose to keep the eco\nnomic mills churning. In the\nfuture economies will be devel\nnpod possibly with less swift\nness than you might expect.\nHow long this tendency can\nbe maintained in the face of\ncontrary pressures\u2014of troops\nto get free, and for setting the\ntreasury in order (tax reduc\ntion remains to be seen.\nm\nSO ALSO with specific recon\nversion policies. For many\nmonths, the popular and undis\nputed public thought has run to\nthe conclusion tHBt the end\nmust bring an economic shock,\nwith widespread unemployment.\nNow the economists are begin\nning to inquire deeper into the\nmatter, seeking to ascertain\nwhat particular types of work\ners and how many in which in\ndustries are being affected\nIn the two largest industries,\nmotors and steel, the highest\npossible peacetime production\nwill be developed as swiftly as\npossible. In those lines much\nunemployment will be tempo\nrary. and of a vacation type i if\nwar bonds have been saved t.\nSHIPBUILDING production,\nfor another instance, will\ndrop near zero, but the Kaiser\nplants on the Pacific Coast, two\nmonths ago. had employment of\nless than 40 per cent of their\npeak. The majority of workers\nknew what was coming and\nwent back home for better jobs.\nAlso Kaiser long since started\nto go into other fields, including\nmotors, and his total peacetime\nemployment may vet run as\nhigh as his wartime peak\nThe large number of women\nworkers who got irito industry\nfor the first time during the\nwar. will find hushands or sup\nporting relatives returning from\nthe war, and may desire to re\nturn to their homes.\n\nr FHE CORF of Iho trouble. I\n1 think, will be found among\nthe migrated unskilled or least\nskilled workers, particularly in\nordnance centers. They came in\ndroves to war manufacturing\nzones from consumer service\njobs, small stores, restaurants,\nhotels, shops, farms and such\nwork for jobs which offered\nmore wages than they had ever\ndreamed of.\nCertainly there exists a tre\nmendous demand for this type\nof worker, back in his former\nendeavors, hack in the shops and\non the farms. Will they want\nto go, is ihe question which\nlooms more important than the\none being popularly asked,\nnamely: will they be ahle to find\njobs\nCertainly the developing prob\nlems are particular rather than\ngeneral, variously affecting dif\nferent types of workers and\nindustries. This points again\nto the theme I have t>oen stress\ning specific remedies are\nneeded rather than an overall\nspending program or similar\ntactics of the Roosevelt regime,\nwhich might create a disastrous\neconomic effect, by encouraging\nthe unemployed to avoid the\njobs where peace so vitally\nneeds them.\nDi\u00bbtrtbut*l by Kin* F>\u00abfur\u00ab* Svnd Inf\nReproduction in \u00bbhole or in part\nitrtctly prohibited\nKnowledge Test\nBy DR. SABINA CONNELLY*\nMff vnortflf 1 tor of the \u2022rtl A*#\nand for the lnl qoettlnn *ror#\n\u2022to brilliant. 7-t brlfht; 4-t. ivtraft;\nO J dull\n1~ How many United States are\nthere in the Western Hemi\nsphere? <a> one; (hi two;\n<ci three\n2 If your friend writes that he\nis sending you vicuna a\u00ab a\nbirthday gift, what would\nyou expect to get? (a* fur;\n\u00abb* jewel*; to) musical in\nstrument\n3 Who\u00abe name is in this in\nscription? \"In this temple,\nas in the hearts of the people\nfor whom he saved the\n1 mon. the memory of\nis enshrined forever.\" <a\u00bb\nGeorge Washington; \u00bbb)\nAbraham Lincoln; <c)\nFtanklin Roosevelt.\n4 One of ihese months is\nnamed after a two-faced god:\n<a* January; (hi February;\nto March\ns\u2014\"Mene, mcne. tekel, uphar\nsin\u2019 are words (a> said by\nChrist at His death: tb*\nwritten on the wall at the\nfeast of Belshazzar; <c\u00bb\ngiven as a signal by Joseph\nto his brothers.\nMatch these columns:\ntil tell the i*> Sf*\u00abtt. R\u00bb4-\n*i r\u2019i t\u00abuntifi\nI T>4 T-nn-w-ft\ntfi, Enoch Arden\nr A' h*U Byron Chi<l*\nlr HuroM Pl\u2019irtmoff\n<1 Th*\n\u00bb*t Ir* r. m\u00bb 4lt\u00bb Lot*\non \u00abrh tn\u00bb\nI dine* f\u00abr\n(Answers on Opposite r&ge)\nCurious Trends in France\nReprint fd-from the July, 19Z$, issue of the Review of World Affairs (memorandum\nof information written and published by Kenneth de Courry, with the help of an\nadvisory committee under the chairmanshp of Lord Phillimore. By special cable\nfrom London.\nIF FRANCE should decline into revolu\ntion and emerge hostile to Britain and\nAmerica, it would be very serious. That\nis the danger. IT IS REAL AND IM\nMINENT. For some reason the facts are\nnot being published anywhere. It is our\nintention to give a frank, very frank\naccount of these affairs.\nWhen one arrives in Paris, one has the\nimpression that it is a refreshingly clean\nand beautiful city, free from the dirt, de\nstruction and war marks which strike\none in nearly all the other great cities of\nEurope.\nThat is the first impression. It lasts\nabout two days. Then slowly it becomes\nclear that something is horribly wrong.\nWar scars would be preferable.\nThe facade hides a state o* affairs\nu)hich is almost unbearable. One longs\nto get away. Coupons mean nothing\nand have no worth. Thf whole country\nis dependent upon a vast expensive\nblack market.\nFood, except bread, is gravely short\nand can be had only at an IMMENSE\nPRICE. Clothes are as bad. A frock\ncosts as much as 25,000 francs and quickly\nwears out.\nReturned prisoners of war can be seen\nabout the streets in rags and without\nmeans. Often they are wearing their old\nprison clothes. Wry many of them have\nbeen influenced bv Nazi philosophy, and\nare POLITICALLY DANGEROUS. Hardly\nany one works for more than three days\na week.\nThe whole country is bedraggled, de\nfeatist, unbelieving, and hopelessly ill-run.\nThere is an uncertain balance between\nextremists of the two brands.\n\nTHE CASE OF LUCIEN FABRE\nMANY people think that the people in\nFrance who are being rounded up,\nlocked up and shot up are collaborators,\ntraitors, men who wanted the Germans to\nwin. The following'story shows what is\nREALLY HAPPENING under the cover\nof that propaganda.\nLucien Fabre is the author of a book\nwhich earned the Prix Goneourt. He popu\nlarized the Einstein theory in France. In\n1939 he was mobilized as an engineer, and\nlater became a director of a factory.\nIn July. 1940, an enemy commission\nturned up to demand the continuation of\nproduction for the Axis powers. Fabre\nrefused pointblank, and his brother, who\nwas director of a neighboring factory, did\nthe same. As the factories were in the\nfree zone, nothing happened.\nAnother commission turned up in\nNovember, 1942, when that zone was\noccupied. Its leader told Fabre that his\nreputation was known. He was accused\nof having helped to enhance the reputa\ntion of a Jew by popularizing jhe\nEinstein theory, that one of his books\nhad been dedicated in words hostile to\nGermany, that he had been a member\nof the league against anti semitism, that\nhe had spoken at Salle Wagram against\npogroms and the Nazi theory, and\nfinally that he had delivered a lecture\nin which he had attached the policies of\nBismarck and Bethmann Holweg.\n\nThe commission then started to boy\ncott his factory by withholding raw ma\nterials. etc. From the time of the armis\ntice to the liberation the Germans did not\nreceive from the firms of Multiplex, or\nFabre and Viguier (the firms directed by\nthe two brothers) one single case of muni\ntions, nor one single uniform jacket.\nFabre\u2019s private house became the hid\ning place of Jews, anti-Fascist Italians and\nThe Experts Bow Out\nTHE war is over and so are the\nlabors of the $55,000 \u201cexperts\u201d\nof the Metropolitan Aviation Plan\nning Authority.\nThis happy combination of cir\ncumstances should be the signal for a\nquick and decisive start on a new\nCity Airport.\nThe end of the war signals action\non all worthwhile projects, hekl in\nabeyance for the duration.\nThe exit of the \u201cexperts\u201d should\nsignal the end of the controversy\nthat has impeded selection of a good\nsite for the airport.\n\nTHE confusion was not lessened as\nthe \u201cexperts\u201d bowed out of the\nairport picture. Their final gesture\nwas to revive the international site\nin Windsor, which in their previous\nreport was an \u201cideal\u201d spot for some\nthing in the future, say about 1960.\nTheir last recommendation was that\nBrain Gamp\nIO for r\u00bbrh rnrrrrt \u00bbnr\u00ab\u00bbr\nIhmorh 20 r\u00bbrh for th# rr\nm\u00bbinlnf t\u00ab\u00bb aurftlnm Anj \u00bbror\u00ab Of\nhifhrr It cirrllrnl. I\n1 \u2014Who is supposed to have\nsaid. \"If the people have no\nhread, let them eat cake\"?\n2 True or false: <a> The fa\nmous Roman. Cicero, is best\nknown ns an orator. tb\u00bb Ac\ncording to the Constitution\nall hills for raising revenue\nshall originate in the Senate\n3 What have \"Carousel.\"\nBloomer Girl/' \"On the\nSpaniards, refugees from the Saar and\nMoselle country, as well as French regis\ntered like schoolmasters and gendarmes.\nNot only were they sheltered, but they\nwere given new identity papers and the\nlike.\nFabre\u2019s brother provided clothes for\nthe Maquis. He trudged roads for thou\nsands of kilometers, collected wool,\narranged for secret spinning, dyeing and\nweaving, and finally for bringing it into\nthe workshop for cutting and finishing.\nNearly all movement had to be at night.\nThere was constant danger from the SS,\nGerman army, the gestapo, the field\npolice and the militiamen.\nThese brothers provided FREE\nEQUIPMENT to the Maquis to the value\nof two million francs. One might have\nthought that that was a great record of\nresistance and patriotism.\n\nWHAT happened? For three months\nfollowing the liberation, the Fabre\nbrothers worked hard to bring the fac\ntories back to normal.\nThere were troubles in that part of\nFrance. Things were not easy. Then\nthere arose a group of criminals, and two\nnames were talked of\u2014a certaiVi Barben\nviande and Rintintin. THIS GANG OF\nCRIMINALS STARTED BY COLLECT\nING THE PERSONAL FORTUNES OF\nVARIOUS COLLABORATORS.\nThis did not prove sufficiently profit\nable.\nOn the sixth of October, 1944, the\nFabre brothers and their partner. Viguier.\nwere arrested WITHOUT CHARGE OR\nREASON. The mystery did not last long\nRintintin arrived at the gendarmerie and\noffered freedom for a ransom of two mil\nlion francs. The prisoners refused.\nThen a Monsieur Clovis was produced,\na well known criminal with a long record\nof convictions for fraud and arson. He\ncame along with an accusation that the\nFabre brothers had stolen an airplane\nengine from a military trailer in 1940, and\nhad then destroyed it.\nThe charge was so flimsy that the\npolice commissioner and the gendarmer\nies lieutenant said they must release the\nprisoner*. When they heard this news\nBarbenviande and Rintintin rushed off\nto the prefect with a trumped-up charge\nthat public opinion demanded these men\nshould be kept in prison.\nSo they were sent to a camp without\ncharge or trial, where they remained for\na month. The Republican commissioner\nwas disturbed at all this, and ordered their\nrelease.\nBut the prefect, who was a crook,\nwarned Rintintin, who rushed to the camp\nwith another effort to screw a ransom\nfrom the wretched prisoners. THIS WAS\nAGAIN REFUSED.\nThen by graft of one kind and another,\nRintintin managed to get the prisoners\ntransferred to another prison, where con\nditions were perfectly frightful, something\nvery near the Nazi mark\nIt was THREE MONTHS AFTER\nTHEIR FIRST ARREST that the prison\ners were able to insist upon being brought\nbefore an examining magistrate, and it\nwit SIX MONTHS BEFORE THEY\nWERE RELEASED.\nThey were received with acclamation\nby the people, and carried home in tri\numph.. But so angry were the terrorists\nthat they completely destroyed the fac\ntories of Fabre and Viguier with bombs.\nThis is one case of very many of the\nsome kind. There is nothing exceptional\nabout it. IT IS UNFORTUNATELY THE\nWAY THINGS HAVE BEEN GOING IN\nFRANCE. That it should all be cloaked\nunder a patriotic purge is sickening.\nthis be made an immediate project of\na permanent Regional Airport Au\nthority, to be set up.\nWe could point out the difficulty\nof trying to convince two govern\nments of the necessity of locating a\nDetroit City Airport in a foreign\ncountry, when we cannot even sell\nthe idea to a few small communities\nin our own backyard.\n\nBUT why add to the Comedy of\nConfusion?\nThere is no time now for bickering\nand academic arguments on where\nthe new airport should go. Air traffic\nis increasing and will increase. It is\nagreed that conditions at the present\nCity Airport border on the danger\nous.\nNow is the time to forget fac\ntional interests and concentrate on\nONE site, the best available, and get\nto work on it.\nTown.\" and \"L'p in Central\nPark\" sh common?\n4 If your skin itches, the irri\ntation may he caused hy: ta>\nlethargy; 'hi antipathy; ic>\nallergy.\n5 <a\u00bb Was the same compovpr\nresponsible for bdth \"A Kiss\nin the Dark\" and Kiss Me\nAgain\"? tht If \u00abo. can you\nname him?\n6 The I'nited States spends a\ngreat deal of money annually\non sports. How much of a\nsports bill would you guess\nthe U. S public paid in the\n\\ears lust before World War\nII *4,000.000. *100.000.000\nor $1000.000.000\u2019\n7 A red sky at sunset indicates\ngood weather, a red skv in\nthe morning promises had.\nWould you say that this be\nlief antedates the establish\nment of weather bureaus?\nR A Scotch city on the river\nClyde is noted for its ship\nbuilding activity. Can you\nname it\nAnswers nn Opposite Page)\nWestbrook\nPegler\n\u2014Fair\nEnough\nSEVERAL statesmen of both\nhouses of Congress have ut\ntered indignant denials of a\ncharge by a psychiatrist at\ntached to a government lunatic\nasylum in Washington that\nCongress drinks too much.\nIf they are right, as my ob\nservation leads me to believe\nthey are, then they are civic\nslackers beefuse it will be re\nmembered that when repeal was\nthe dominating issue of the 1932\nelection, those who were op\nposed to prohibition took an\nobligation to drink our beloved\nnation out of debt.\nThe taxes to the federal, state,\ncounty and municipal- govern\nments would swell the treasuries\nand unemployment would be\nabolished as men were absorbed\ninto the breweries, distilleries,\nglass-works for the manufac\nture of bottles and glasses of va\nrious shapes, the cork factories\nand bottling plants and the hos\npitals for service as attendants\nto honorable casualties in this\nphase of our war on want.\n\nII r E HAD figures to prove it,\ntoo, and the failure of tjus\nsolution to solve the problems\nwhich it was designed to solve\nis almost enough to destroy\none s faith in simple arithmetic.\nNothing was solved even\nthough we became the hard\ndrinkingest people in the world\nand even though all those pre\ndictions did come true about the\nabsorption of toilers into the\nbeer and liquor trades\nRut it would be a cruel injus\ntice to blame the people for\nthe failure because the statistici\nand the recent growth of inter\nest -in clinics for incbriatea\nprove that we have tried.\n\nMY ACQUAINTANCE among\nCongress is a reliable sam\npling and I have to say that\ni these patriots ha\\e not stood to\nthe bar as faithfully as some\nother groups\nOn a recent afternoon, when\nthe bell had rung and school\nwas out, so to speak, a Repub\nj bean statesman pulled out the\ndrawer of his desk producing a\nquart of squeezing and two\nglasses and we had two apiece.\n'lTien he pht the equipment\nhack, (hewed a clo\\e and dro\\e\nexpertly home to dinner\nOthers of my acquaint ange\ndrink no more and some drink\nless or not at all and since the\ndeath of a rather dashing west\nern toy-pot who ranked high\ntn foreign relations and occa\nsionally twisted the lion\u2019s tail\nor plucked sprigs from the\nbeard of the Communist menace\nwhile high in his drarm. some\ntimes to the alarm of his col\nleagues, I have heard of no\ni statesman on the Hill with a\n1 reputation comparable to those\nof some of our more noted po\nlitical .spokesmen for the art*.\n\nZ' 1 LANCINC hack. T am in\nclined to hold that it is up\nto the younger generation to\ndo the hea\\y drinking if they\nwould preserve the victory\nwhich we of the prohibition\nera won for them in a long and\npainful contest with\nWayne R Wheeler, Rishop Can\nnon Derts Picket and the Rev.\nClarence True Wilson a dry\nwho was the bosom friend of\n(\u2019larente Harrow, a wet. and\nsometimes traveled with him to\ndebates, sharing a drawing\nroom, one with a tumbler of\nmilk on the table between\nthem as they went over thejr\nlines, the other with a glass\nof Maryland com\n\nj HAVE been inspecting my\nI conscience and suspect that I\nwas insincere in stating in those\ndays that if we could have beer\nagain and light wine we would\nall become temperate and con\ntent\nThe corner saloon, we said,\nmust never come back, hut that\nwas a technicality for the sa\nloon in the middle of the block\ni* still a saloon\nAs soon as the licenses could\nbe cleared up were shoving\ncocktails of atomic strength in\ndairy lunchrooms right theje in\nWashington and through 1 the\nagency of young waitresses, at\nthat\nWe never had waitresses In\nthe old corner saloon and lady\ntrade was strirtly forbidden ex-\nI rp pf in ihe palm room back he\nhind Rut the di\u00abfaff had joined\nus in flouting the foul amend\nment over the bflter years and\ntheir score of hang-over and\nulcers had earned them a right\nto become maudlin, untidy and\nidiotic on equality with the men.\n\nQJf) FALLIBLE and emotional\nj is memory that the dries\nI blame and the wets among us\npraise Franklin D. Roosevelt for\nrepeal when the contest is re\ncalled at all and moat opinion\nholds that the New Deal, the\nmoney changers in the temple\nand national recovery domi\nnated that campaign of 1932.\nActually, the issue was pro\nhibition which Mr. Hoovae\nlacked the political wfsrfbm to\ndisown and Roosevelt was\nelected as a wet.\nBut he was not a wet until\nAl Smith had carried the ban\nner and had been riddled by\nsuch dries as William McAdoo\nand Cordell Hull who were\nRoosevelt men.\nAnd. because he had taken ne\nstand himself on the issue of\nrepeal the convention dispersed\nj very doubtful of his ability t\u00bb\n1 carry his own state, much lest\nthe nation.\nCopTrifht. I*4 9 9* Kini Pn*mi","height":"27996","width":"21450"}}
